# SVG modifications: use svg.js

When modifying, creating, or manipulating SVG content in this project, **always use the [@svgdotjs/svg.js](https://svgjs.com/) library** instead of raw DOM or manual attribute strings.

- **Get the root instance** via `SvgManipulationService.getSVGInstance()` (returns `Svg | null`).
- **Find elements** with `svgInstance.findOne('#id')` or `svgInstance.find('selector')`.
- **Mutate shapes** using SVG.js methods (e.g. `shape.fill()`, `shape.dmove()`, `shape.attr()`, `shape.clone()`) rather than `element.setAttribute()` or `element.style`.
- **Create new SVG structures** with `SVG()`, `SVG(domElement)`, or shape constructors (e.g. `.rect()`, `.circle()`) from the library, not `document.createElementNS('http://www.w3.org/2000/svg', ...)` for elements that live inside the canvas.

This keeps behavior consistent, avoids duplication of logic, and ensures transforms/attributes are applied in a way the rest of the app expects.

## Exception: pure geometry helpers in `models/`

Files under `src/app/models/` that are pure math/geometry utilities (e.g. `outline-to-path.ts`, `path-boolean.ts`) may use `document.createElementNS` and `setAttribute` to construct transient `<path>` elements solely for geometry computation — these elements are never inserted into the live canvas. This is intentional: these helpers are framework-agnostic and must not import svg.js. Do not treat these as violations when reviewing.
